Wonderful advise! Thank u so much Prof. Ayazifar!

Thank you Babak for the suggestions! Sadly, turned out that 126 and 127 have the exact same lecture time for Fall 2019. I really hope that one of the lecture time can be changed, but if not Plan 2 is good too.

I assume by "Spring 2019" you actually mean Spring 2020.

Linear algebra ... you can pick up on your own.

Probability ... much, much harder to pick up on your own, especially at the 126 level.

Plan 1 (Ideal Plan, IMHO): Make room for both 126 and 127 next fall. Do NOT take any other technical if you execute this plan. If you don't heed the admonition in bold, underline, and italics (the redundant combination of which is for emphasis), you'd be guilty of GPA euthanasia, among other things.

This plan will give you a serious edge when you take ML next spring.

Plan 2: Take 126 next fall.  But in the summer, go over Stanford Professor Stephen Boyd's course and book on convex optimization.  He is legendary. His most recent videos are behind a firewall, but his circa 2007-8 videos are available here:

http://web.stanford.edu/class/ee364a/videos.html

And he ALWAYS makes the PDF of his textbooks available for free.  You can find it here:

http://web.stanford.edu/~boyd/cvxbook/

In fact, if you go to the book link above, you'll find another link to a 2014 MOOC of the course that he offered. You should then be all set. 

I don't know if Laurent and Gireeja are webcasting 127 this spring, but if they do, you might want to take their course.  It should be a more modern take than the publicly-visible Stanford counterpart.  Doing that will also give you a good piece of Stephen Boyd's legacy, since Laurent was his PhD student.

I hope my dear colleague Anant will chime in, since he has actually taught and redesigned 189 and is in a much better position to comment.

Upshot: If you want an edge, you must go beyond the minimum required, whether that be next fall or this summer specifically, or in life more generally.

Regards,

Babak.

history.content:
According to the draft schedule, Professor Shewchuk is teaching 189 in Spring 2020. I'm in his 189 right now, and by far the most important areas prereq-wise have been linear algebra at the 127 level along with a strong grasp on vector calculus (gradients etc.) and probability (gaussian distributions, techniques related to expectation, covariance etc.). 

The most ideal preparation for 189 in the Spring would be 126 and 127 in the Fall, like Babak suggested. However, if you do not have the bandwidth for 126, you should take Prob 140. There isn't really any alternative to 127 in so far as application-based linear algebra is concerned. I'm assuming you've already done Math 53, which covers vector calculus, and EE 16AB, which provide the linear algebra foundation for 127. 

If you can only take one course, take 126. It will help build your intuition for probability, something hard to do independently. Self-study linear algebra from other sources like Stephen Boyd's course or cover the concepts at http://gwthomas.github.io/docs/math4ml.pdf independently in more detail.

=======

I haven't taken 189, so I don't know which is most useful for it (especially since it seems like different professors place emphasis on different things from what I read on here). That said, I have taken all 3 classes you listed - EECS 126, EECS 127 (currently in it), Math 110 - and I'll say that 126 is by far the hardest to self-study of the three, and also the most I've ever gotten out of a single class here. I highly recommend it be your choice if you can only take one of the three. Contrary to what I thought going in, it's not a class on really hard probability questions. The class title also has "random processes" in it for a reason, and spends only the first third on raw 70-esque probability theory with a few new topics thrown in (MGFs, convergence of random variables). The other 2/3 of it goes over the Poisson Process, MLE/MAP estimation, Kalman filtering, and other topics that I've seen come up in several contexts that have nothing to do with machine learning.

After 126, I think 127 is the next hardest to self-study. One of the "intangibles" 127 gives you is getting very comfortable with long derivations and manipulations centered around matrix calculus and algebra, both doing them yourself and reading them when you have to understand something. 110, as with most math classes here (from what I'm told), has a lot of variance based on the professor teaching. I had Frenkel, who re-covered a lot of topics I had seen before in 16AB and 54, but from the abstract, axiomatic perspective, and it gave me a chance to really internalize them, which I got a lot out of. I have a friend taking it now with Holtz and the problems he's showed me on his homework are significantly harder than what I remember. If you have a reasonable background from 16AB and/or 54, I think picking up either Axler's or Friedberg's textbook (we used Friedberg, and I thought it was good and has a lot of good practice problems, but I know a lot of people like Axler; I've never read it so I can't comment) and reading through the chapters and doing the end of chapter problems can get you up to speed there.

Another option, if you don't have time for 127, is to study Stephen Boyd's other course EE 103 at Stanford:

http://web.stanford.edu/class/ee103/

As I mentioned in my previous post, his textbook PDF is available there for free.  He designed this course as a linear algebra intro that can catapult you into a zillion applications, including ML.  The linear algebra is elementary in most parts (though it has a freshness throughout). You have to be selective in what you study from the book, or you might get bored---given that you've taken a linear algebra course before. 

I recommend that you dive straight into Chapter 4, and then skip to Part III and study it carefully (skipping the parts that you've seen before in 16A/B or 54). 

Camouflaged on his course site is the "Slides" link, under which you'll find a wealth applications to expose yourself to.

http://web.stanford.edu/class/ee103/lectures.html

Don't be disappointed if some of the links on the EE 103 page are available only to the Stanford community. What I've described above is open to the public.

Regards,


Babak.
